# Local development without the LaraKube CLI

This project runs on Kubernetes. Its manifests were generated by
[LaraKube](https://larakube.luchtech.dev) and live in `.infrastructure/k8s/`.

You **don't have to install the LaraKube binary** to run it locally. The
`larakube.sh` script in this folder is a small, auditable wrapper around
`kubectl` and `docker` that covers the day-to-day local workflow. Read it —
it's ~150 lines of plain bash, no magic.

> Prefer the full experience (automatic cluster setup, TLS trust, hosts
> management, manifest regeneration)? Install the LaraKube CLI instead.
> `larakube.sh` is the no-install option for contributors.

## Requirements

On your own machine:

- A **local Kubernetes cluster** with `kubectl` pointed at it
  (Docker Desktop, OrbStack, k3s, k3d, kind, or minikube all work).
- **docker** — used to build the local image.
- **jq** — used to read `.larakube.json`.

Verify:

```bash
kubectl version --client
docker --version
jq --version
kubectl config current-context   # make sure this is your LOCAL cluster
```

## First run

1. Put the project's `.env` at the repo root (ask a teammate / your password
   manager — it's not committed).
2. Bring it up:

   ```bash
   ./larakube.sh up
   ```

   This builds the image, applies `.infrastructure/k8s/overlays/local`, syncs
   your `.env` into the cluster, and starts the pods. Watch progress with
   `./larakube.sh status`.

## Commands

```
./larakube.sh list           # show this list

# Lifecycle
up                           # build + apply manifests + restart pods
start | stop                 # scale up / down (stop keeps your data)
down                         # delete the namespace (asks to confirm)
build                        # build the image only

# Dev loop
watch                        # reload Octane/Horizon/queues on file change
reload                       # reload once, now
artisan <args>               # e.g. ./larakube.sh artisan migrate
composer <args>              # e.g. ./larakube.sh composer install
npm <args>                   # e.g. ./larakube.sh npm run dev

# Local URLs (app + Vite HMR + Reverb over https://*.dev.test)
hosts                        # map ingress hosts → 127.0.0.1 in /etc/hosts (sudo)
tls                          # make the cluster's Traefik serve the local cert
trust                        # trust the local CA so HTTPS is valid (sudo)

# Introspection
status                       # pods / services / ingress
logs [deploy]                # tail logs (default: web)
shell [deploy]               # shell into a pod (default: web)
forward [port]               # quick web-only check (does NOT cover Vite/Reverb)
```

## Reaching the app in a browser

The app, Vite (HMR), and Reverb (WebSockets) are each served on their own
ingress hostname (`<project>.dev.test`, `vite-…`, `reverb-…`). To use them you
need three one-time things — after a normal `up`:

```bash
./larakube.sh tls      # cluster Traefik serves the LaraKube local cert
./larakube.sh trust    # your machine trusts that cert (sudo)
./larakube.sh hosts    # *.dev.test → 127.0.0.1 in /etc/hosts (sudo)
# then open: https://<project>.dev.test
```

Notes:
- **`tls` needs an ingress controller already running.** k3s ships Traefik, so
  it works out of the box; on Docker Desktop/OrbStack you'd install one first
  (or use the LaraKube CLI, which sets this up for you).
- **`trust` matters for Reverb.** Browsers reject self-signed certs on
  WebSocket (WSS) connections silently, so Reverb won't connect until the cert
  is trusted.
- **`forward` is only a shortcut** for "is the web app up?" on simple apps — it
  port-forwards the web pod to `http://localhost:8080` and does NOT route Vite
  or Reverb. Use the three commands above for real local dev.

## Good to know

- **It does not regenerate manifests.** Editing `.larakube.json` and running
  `larakube heal` is a CLI-only operation. `larakube.sh` *consumes* the
  committed manifests; it never rewrites them. If the blueprint changes, pull
  the updated `.infrastructure/k8s/` from version control.
- **Everything is local.** The script only ever touches the
  `<project>-local` namespace.
- **Code changes:** JS hot-reloads via Vite (`./larakube.sh npm run dev`).
  PHP changes are picked up by `./larakube.sh watch` (or a one-off
  `./larakube.sh reload`).

## Troubleshooting

- **Pods stuck in `ImagePullBackOff`** — your cluster can't see the locally
  built image. Docker Desktop/OrbStack share images automatically; k3d/kind/
  minikube are auto-imported by `up`. For **k3s** (containerd), import once:

  ```bash
  docker save <project>:latest | sudo k3s ctr images import -
  ```

- **`No '<deploy>' deployment` errors** — the project isn't up yet; run
  `./larakube.sh up`.
- **Browser can't resolve the hostname** — run `./larakube.sh hosts`. For a
  quick web-only peek without DNS/TLS, `./larakube.sh forward` →
  `http://localhost:8080` (no Vite/Reverb).
- **Reverb won't connect / HTTPS warnings** — run `./larakube.sh tls` then
  `./larakube.sh trust`, and restart your browser.
- **Wrong cluster** — `kubectl config current-context` should point at your
  local cluster before running anything.
